The variables stra and surf did not have statistically significant effect against points. However, the variable Attitude showed a significant effect against points do lets remove them. The adjusted R-squared of the model was 0.19, indicating that 19 % of the variation in exam points was explained by the explanatory variables.

If an explanatory variable in your model does not have a statistically significant relationship with the target variable, remove the variable from the model and fit the model again without it

I removed stra and surf from the explanatory variables.

Explain the assumptions of the model

The model allows to makes the 4 main assumptions:

  • Linear relationship: The explanatory variable X and the dependent variable Y show a linear relationship.
  • independence of residuals: The residuals should be independent. -normal distribution of residuals : the observations look normally distributed around the fitted line
  • Equal variance of residuals: the distance between observations from the fitted line should be the same on the left and right sides

Interpret the validity of those assumptions based on the diagnostic plots

  • Linear relationship: We observe a linear relationship between the variable X and Y according to the plot of residuals VS fitted values .
  • independence of residuals: Observations are independent of each other.
  • normal distribution of residuals : the observations look normally distributed according to the Q-Q plot
  • Equal variance of residuals: the variance of the residual is the same for each value of the dependent variable,indicating that the data is in homoscedasticity.

#3 hypothesis I choose the variables school,sex,address, Pstatus to investigate whether the school, the gender, the home address type, the parents cohabitation status affect the low/high alcohol consumption. I hypothesize that man, people studying in one of the two school, living in urban area, with parents apart, drink more alcohol than women, people studying in the other school, living in rural areas, with parents together, respectively.

For address, urban area had a negative coefficient which indicate a decrease of the odd ratio for address of students. The odds ratio of 2.52 for sex Male indicates that the odds of high alcohol use for males are approximately 2.52 times higher than for females.
